[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         E -->|Trajectories| H[Step Functions: Training Pipeline]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         H -->|Train| I[SageMaker: Offline RL Training]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         I -->|Model| J[S3: Model Registry]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         H -->|Evaluate| K[SageMaker: Simulator Evaluation]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Inference
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         G -->|Read State| L[Lambda: Policy Inference]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         J -->|Load Model| L
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         L -->|Recommendations| M[Operations Dashboard]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     subgraph Feedback
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         M -->|Decisions| N[Outcome Tracker]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         N -->|Log| E
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     end
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style L fill:#9f9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, AWS Step Functions, Amazon Kinesis, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon S3, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateEndpoint`, `kinesis:GetRecords`, `kinesis:PutRecord`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `lambda:InvokeFunction`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | Required: patient census data, acuity scores, and ADT feeds contain PHI |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for training data; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; Kinesis: server-side encryption; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda + SageMaker in VPC with endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, Kinesis, CloudWatch Logs. SageMaker training in private subnet. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all SageMaker, Lambda, and DynamoDB API calls |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic hospital operational data. MIMIC-IV provides realistic ICU census patterns for development. Never use real patient data in dev environments. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker training: $500-3,000/month (GPU instances during training runs); Kinesis: $50-200/month; DynamoDB: $100-300/month; Lambda inference: $50-200/month; S3: $50-100/month |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | RL model training (offline CQL/BCQ), hyperparameter tuning, model hosting for batch evaluation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates training pipeline: data prep, training, evaluation, approval gates, deployment |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis** | Real-time ingestion of ADT events, staffing changes, and census updates |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores current hospital state for real-time policy inference |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | State aggregation from event stream; policy inference for recommendations |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Training data lake (historical trajectories), model artifacts, simulation logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Operational metrics, recommendation acceptance tracking, drift detection alarms |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for PHI in transit and at rest |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: State representation engineering.** The first (and arguably most important) step is defining what the RL agent "sees" at each decision point. The state must capture everything relevant to resource allocation while being compact enough for a neural network to process efficiently. You'll aggregate information from multiple hospital systems into a single state vector. Each dimension represents something operationally meaningful: current occupancy ratios, staff-to-patient ratios, pending arrivals, time features, and equipment availability. Get this wrong and the agent is literally blind to the factors that matter. The feature engineering here is where domain expertise from hospital operations staff is irreplaceable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION build_state_vector(timestamp):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Gather current hospital state from all operational systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Each piece of this state affects what allocation decisions are feasible and optimal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state = empty vector
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // BED OCCUPANCY: Current census by unit type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Ratio (0.0 to 1.0) tells the agent how much capacity remains
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each unit_type in [ICU, StepDown, MedSurg, Telemetry, ED, PACU]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         occupied = count beds currently occupied in unit_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total    = count total licensed beds in unit_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.append(occupied / total)  // occupancy ratio
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // PENDING MOVEMENTS: Patients in transition (these beds will free up or fill soon)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(count patients with pending discharge orders today)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(count patients awaiting bed assignment in ED)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(count patients in PACU awaiting floor bed)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(count scheduled surgical cases remaining today)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // STAFFING: Current nurse-to-patient ratios by unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each unit_type in [ICU, StepDown, MedSurg, Telemetry, ED]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         nurses_on = count nurses currently clocked in for unit_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patients  = count patients in unit_type
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.append(nurses_on / max(patients, 1))  // ratio; higher is better
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // TIME FEATURES: Cyclical encoding captures daily/weekly patterns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     hour_of_day = extract hour from timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     day_of_week = extract weekday from timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(sin(2 * pi * hour_of_day / 24))  // cyclical hour encoding
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(cos(2 * pi * hour_of_day / 24))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(sin(2 * pi * day_of_week / 7))   // cyclical day encoding
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(cos(2 * pi * day_of_week / 7))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // DEMAND FORECAST: Short-term expected arrivals (from time series model)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(predicted ED arrivals next 4 hours)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(predicted ED arrivals next 8 hours)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // EQUIPMENT: Critical resource availability
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(available ventilators / total ventilators)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     state.append(available telemetry monitors / total monitors)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ACUITY MIX: Distribution of patient severity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each acuity_level in [1_Critical, 2_Acute, 3_Moderate, 4_Low]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         state.append(count patients at acuity_level / total_patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN state  // Vector of ~35-50 dimensions depending on hospital complexity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Action space definition.** The agent needs a discrete set of actions it can propose at each decision point. Hospital resource allocation involves many simultaneous micro-decisions, but for RL to work, we need to decompose this into manageable action sets. The approach: define a fixed set of allocation "moves" and let the agent choose among them. Hard safety constraints are enforced by masking: actions that would violate safety rules are simply removed from consideration before the agent chooses. This guarantees constraint satisfaction without relying on the agent to learn the constraints through negative reward.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m // Define the action space for bed assignment decisions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ACTIONS = [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "assign_to_icu",           // Place patient in ICU
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "assign_to_stepdown",      // Place patient in step-down unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "assign_to_medsurg",       // Place patient in med-surg
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "assign_to_telemetry",     // Place patient in telemetry
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "hold_in_ed",              // Keep patient in ED (wait for better option)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "expedite_discharge",      // Flag a current patient for expedited discharge review
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "activate_overflow",       // Open surge/overflow capacity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "request_transfer_out",    // Initiate transfer to another facility
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "call_additional_staff",   // Request additional nursing staff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "defer_elective"           // Recommend postponing a scheduled elective case
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION get_valid_actions(state, patient_context):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Mask out actions that violate hard safety constraints.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // The agent CANNOT select a masked action. Period.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     valid = copy of ACTIONS
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Cannot assign to a unit that's at 100% capacity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF icu_occupancy(state) >= 1.0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove "assign_to_icu" from valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF stepdown_occupancy(state) >= 1.0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove "assign_to_stepdown" from valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Cannot assign high-acuity patient to low-acuity unit
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF patient_context.acuity == CRITICAL:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove "assign_to_medsurg" from valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove "assign_to_telemetry" from valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Cannot call additional staff if already at maximum on-call pool
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF on_call_pool_exhausted():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove "call_additional_staff" from valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Cannot defer elective if patient is already in OR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF no_deferrable_electives_remaining():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         remove "defer_elective" from valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN valid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Reward function design.** This is where the art lives. The reward function defines what "good" means. In hospital resource allocation, good is multi-dimensional: efficient use of resources, low wait times, balanced workloads, maintained surge capacity, and (most importantly) good patient outcomes. The reward is computed at each time step based on how the hospital state evolved after the action was taken. Getting this right requires iteration with clinical operations leaders. The weights (how much you value throughput vs. safety margin vs. staff wellbeing) are policy decisions, not technical ones. Expect to tune these extensively.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION compute_reward(state_before, action, state_after, outcomes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reward = 0.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // THROUGHPUT: Reward for successfully placing a patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF action resulted in patient receiving bed within target time:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward += 10.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELIF patient is still waiting:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hours_waiting = time since patient arrived
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= 2.0 * hours_waiting  // escalating penalty
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // OCCUPANCY BALANCE: Penalize extreme over- or under-utilization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each unit_type:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         occ = occupancy_ratio(state_after, unit_type)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF occ > 0.95:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reward -= 15.0 * (occ - 0.95)  // steep penalty above 95%
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELIF occ > 0.85:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reward -= 3.0 * (occ - 0.85)   // mild penalty above 85%
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELIF occ < 0.50:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reward -= 2.0 * (0.50 - occ)   // penalty for waste
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // STAFF WORKLOAD: Penalize unsafe ratios
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each unit_type:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ratio = nurse_to_patient_ratio(state_after, unit_type)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF ratio < minimum_safe_ratio(unit_type):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reward -= 50.0  // severe penalty for safety violation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // SURGE CAPACITY: Reward maintaining buffer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     icu_buffer = 1.0 - icu_occupancy(state_after)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF icu_buffer >= 0.15:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward += 5.0   // reward for keeping 15%+ ICU buffer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELIF icu_buffer < 0.05:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= 20.0  // severe penalty for near-zero ICU margin
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // OUTCOME PROXY: Penalize boarding (patients stuck in wrong unit)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     boarding_hours = count_ed_boarding_hours(state_after)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reward -= 1.5 * boarding_hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // OUTCOME PROXY: Penalize unnecessary transfers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF action == "transfer" AND patient_was_stable:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         reward -= 5.0  // transfers have costs and risks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Offline policy training.** With state, action, and reward defined, you train the RL policy on historical trajectories. Each trajectory is a sequence of (state, action, reward, next_state) tuples extracted from your hospital's operational history. The offline RL algorithm (CQL in this example) learns a policy that would have achieved high reward on the historical data while being conservative about actions it hasn't seen evidence for. Training runs on GPU instances and typically takes hours to days depending on data volume and model complexity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION train_offline_policy(trajectories, config):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // trajectories: list of episodes, each a sequence of (s, a, r, s') tuples
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // config: hyperparameters (learning rate, CQL alpha, discount factor, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Initialize the policy network (actor) and value network (critic)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     policy_network = initialize_neural_network(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         input_dim  = state_dimension,       // ~35-50 features
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output_dim = number_of_actions,     // ~10 possible actions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hidden     = [256, 256, 128]        // 3 hidden layers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     q_network = initialize_neural_network(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         input_dim  = state_dimension + action_dimension,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         output_dim = 1,                     // scalar Q-value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         hidden     = [256, 256, 128]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // CQL adds a penalty term to prevent overestimation of out-of-distribution actions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cql_alpha = config.cql_alpha  // typically 1.0-5.0; higher = more conservative
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each training_iteration in range(config.num_iterations):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Sample a batch of transitions from historical data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         batch = sample_random_batch(trajectories, batch_size=256)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Standard Bellman backup for Q-learning
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each (state, action, reward, next_state) in batch:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             target_q = reward + config.gamma * max_q(q_network, next_state, valid_actions(next_state))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // CQL penalty: push down Q-values for actions NOT in the dataset
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // This makes the agent conservative about novel actions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cql_loss = cql_alpha * (expected_q_under_policy - expected_q_under_data)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Combined loss: standard TD error + CQL regularization
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_loss = td_loss(q_network, batch, target_q) + cql_loss
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update q_network with gradient of total_loss
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         update policy_network to maximize Q-values for in-distribution actions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Periodically evaluate in simulator
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF training_iteration % eval_interval == 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             sim_reward = evaluate_in_simulator(policy_network, num_episodes=100)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             log("Iteration {}, Simulator Reward: {}", training_iteration, sim_reward)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN policy_network
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Simulation-based evaluation.** Before deploying recommendations to real operations, validate the learned policy extensively in a discrete-event simulator. The simulator models patient arrivals, length of stay, acuity changes, staffing patterns, and operational constraints. It should be calibrated against your hospital's actual data. Run thousands of simulated days under the learned policy and compare against baseline (the historical policy). Look for constraint violations, edge cases (surge scenarios, mass casualty events), and distributional outcomes, not just averages.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION evaluate_policy_in_simulator(policy, simulator_config, num_episodes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR episode in range(num_episodes):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Initialize simulator with realistic starting conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sim = HospitalSimulator(config=simulator_config)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         sim.initialize_from_historical_distribution()  // random but realistic start
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         total_reward = 0.0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         constraint_violations = 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         wait_times = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         occupancy_history = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Run one simulated day (or week, depending on evaluation scope)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHILE sim.time < sim.end_time:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Get current state from simulator
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             state = sim.get_state_vector()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             valid_actions = get_valid_actions(state, sim.current_patient_context())
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Ask policy for recommended action
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             action = policy.select_action(state, valid_actions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Execute action in simulator; observe outcome
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             reward, next_state, info = sim.step(action)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             total_reward += reward
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF info.constraint_violated:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 constraint_violations += 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             wait_times.append(info.patient_wait_time)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             occupancy_history.append(info.occupancy_by_unit)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Record episode summary
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             total_reward:          total_reward,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             constraint_violations: constraint_violations,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             mean_wait_time:        mean(wait_times),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             p95_wait_time:         percentile(wait_times, 95),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             mean_occupancy:        mean(occupancy_history),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             surge_capacity_maintained: min(icu_buffer in occupancy_history) > 0.05
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Aggregate across episodes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mean_reward:                   mean(r.total_reward for r in results),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mean_constraint_violations:    mean(r.constraint_violations for r in results),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mean_wait_time:                mean(r.mean_wait_time for r in results),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         p95_wait_time:                 mean(r.p95_wait_time for r in results),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         surge_maintained_pct:          count(r.surge_capacity_maintained for r in results) / num_episodes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         worst_case_violations:         max(r.constraint_violations for r in results)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Deployment as recommendation engine.** The trained policy runs inference against real-time hospital state and surfaces recommendations to human operators. This is explicitly not autonomous control. The charge nurse or bed manager sees the recommendation, applies their own judgment, and makes the final call. The system tracks acceptance rates, overrides, and outcomes for both followed and rejected recommendations. This data feeds the next training cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION generate_recommendation(current_state, patient_context):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Load trained policy model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     policy = load_model_from_registry("hospital-allocation-policy", version="latest")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Get valid actions given constraints
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     valid_actions = get_valid_actions(current_state, patient_context)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Get action probabilities from policy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     action_probs = policy.predict(current_state, valid_actions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Return top-3 recommendations with confidence scores
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     top_actions = sort_by_probability(action_probs, descending=True)[:3]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recommendation = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         timestamp:       current_utc_time(),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:      patient_context.id,       // de-identified for logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         current_state:   summarize_state(current_state),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         recommendations: [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 action:      top_actions[0].action,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence:  top_actions[0].probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rationale:   explain_action(top_actions[0], current_state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 action:      top_actions[1].action,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence:  top_actions[1].probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rationale:   explain_action(top_actions[1], current_state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 action:      top_actions[2].action,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence:  top_actions[2].probability,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rationale:   explain_action(top_actions[2], current_state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         constraints_active: list_active_constraints(current_state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store for tracking (even if human overrides)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     store_recommendation(recommendation)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN recommendation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter15.10-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample recommendation output:**
