[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks (simulation evaluation):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Baseline (Historical Policy) | RL Policy | Improvement |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|------------------------------|-----------|-------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Mean patient wait (ED to bed) | 4.2 hours | 2.8 hours | 33% reduction |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | ICU buffer maintained (>10%) | 71% of time | 89% of time | +18 percentage points |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Staff overtime hours/week | 142 | 108 | 24% reduction |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Occupancy balance (std dev across units) | 0.14 | 0.09 | 36% improvement |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Constraint violations per week | 3.2 | 0.4 | 87% reduction |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | ED boarding hours per week | 87 | 52 | 40% reduction |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Rare catastrophic events (mass casualty incidents, pandemic surges) that aren't well-represented in training data. Rapidly changing hospital configurations (new unit opens, renovations). Staff behavioral changes that don't match historical patterns. Seasonal shifts in patient mix that haven't been seen before in training data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    559[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    560[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    561[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    562[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    563[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Simulator fidelity.** The entire validation approach depends on your discrete-event simulator accurately modeling your hospital. If the simulator's length-of-stay distributions are wrong, if it doesn't model discharge delays realistically, or if it ignores ED-to-inpatient boarding dynamics, your policy may perform well in simulation and poorly in reality. Building and calibrating a hospital simulator is itself a multi-month project.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reward function alignment.** The reward weights encode your hospital's values. Getting them wrong means optimizing for the wrong thing. If you weight throughput too heavily relative to staff wellbeing, the policy will recommend actions that burn out nurses. These weights need clinical operations leadership input and iterative refinement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Distribution shift monitoring.** The hospital environment changes: new construction, service line additions, staffing model changes, pandemic surges. The offline-trained policy assumes a stationary environment. You need drift detection that alerts when the current state distribution diverges significantly from training data distribution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    570[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    571[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    572[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    573[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let me be direct: this is the hardest recipe in the book. Not because the RL algorithms are particularly exotic (CQL and BCQ are well-documented), but because the engineering surrounding the RL model is enormous.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    574[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    575[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The simulation environment alone is a 6-12 month build. You're essentially recreating your hospital's operational dynamics in code. Every shortcut you take (simplifying patient flow, ignoring transfers between units, assuming deterministic discharge times) introduces model error that will show up as policy failures.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    576[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    577[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The reward function will be wrong on your first attempt. And your second. And probably your fifth. Getting clinical operations leaders to articulate what they actually value (as opposed to what they say they value) is a facilitation challenge as much as a technical one. "We want to maximize throughput while maintaining safety" sounds clear until you ask: "Would you rather have a 5% shorter wait time or a 3% larger ICU buffer?" The answer depends on context, and that context-dependence is exactly what the RL agent needs to learn.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    578[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    579[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The part that surprised me most: the human factors dominate the technical challenges. A charge nurse with 20 years of experience will reject a recommendation from a black-box model, even if it's correct, unless they understand why. Explainability isn't a nice-to-have. It's a deployment prerequisite.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    580[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    581[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Start with Recipe 14.6 (Patient Flow / Bed Assignment) using traditional optimization. Get that working. Then layer RL on top for the dynamic, uncertain aspects that optimization handles poorly. Don't build the RL system first and hope it works.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    582[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    585[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    586[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    587[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-facility coordination.** Extend the state and action space to include multiple hospitals in a health system. Actions include inter-facility transfers and load balancing. The state space grows substantially, but the payoff is system-level optimization instead of local-hospital optimization. Multi-agent RL is the natural framework: one agent per facility, shared reward for system-level metrics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    588[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    589[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pandemic surge planning.** Train the policy on synthetic surge scenarios (generated by running your simulator with dramatically elevated arrival rates). This gives the agent experience with extreme states it's unlikely to see in normal historical data. The challenge: you're training on simulated extremes, so the quality of your surge model directly determines whether the policy is useful during an actual surge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    590[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    591[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration with discharge prediction.** Connect the RL agent's state with a predictive model for discharge timing (see Recipe 7.7: Length of Stay Prediction). Instead of using average length-of-stay distributions, feed the RL state with per-patient discharge probability forecasts. This gives the agent much more accurate forward visibility into when beds will free up.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    592[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    593[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    594[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    595[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    596[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    597[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.6 (Patient Flow / Bed Assignment):** The deterministic optimization version of this problem. Start here before adding RL.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    598[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.3 (ED Arrival Forecasting):** The demand forecast that feeds into the RL agent's state vector.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    599[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.5 (Hospital Census Forecasting):** Provides predicted occupancy trajectories that inform surge capacity decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    600[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.7 (Length of Stay Prediction):** Per-patient discharge predictions that sharpen the agent's view of future capacity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    601[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.4 (Nurse Staffing Optimization):** The staff allocation sub-problem that interacts with bed assignment decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    602[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 15.1 (Alert Threshold Optimization):** A simpler RL recipe to build team expertise before tackling this complex problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    603[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    604[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
